Bibliographic Essay

January 07 2018

Historical

It is hard to believe that, prior to about 1920, there were many who considered Mendelian genetics to be incompatible with Darwinian Evolution. It was the seminal work of, among others, R. A. Fisher, J. B. S. Haldane and Sewall Wright that led to their reconciliation and what is now known as the “Modern Synthesis” of evolutionary biology. The late historian, biologist and iconolclast Will Provine wrote of the early days of that period of resolution; the book that resulted from his Master’s thesis (William B. Provine 2001) is well worth reading. Provine also wrote a seminal biography of Sewall Wright, one of the greatest geneticists of the twentieth century (William B Provine 1986).

James Crow and his then student Motoo Kimura. Copyright Genetics Society of America

Two of the most important academic lineages were those of Theodosius Dobzhansky and James Crow. Dobzhansky and his colleagues focused more on empirical population genetics, while Crow and his students (particular Motoo Kimura) made seminal contributions to the theoretical underpinnings of the field. Two good places to start are with Dobzhansky’s Genetics of the Evolutionary Process(Dobzhansky 1970) and Kimura’s The Neutral Theory of Evolution(M. Kimura 1985). For those who wish to delve deeper into their original work, collected volumes of Dobzhansky’s (Lewontin et al. 1981) and Kimura’s (M. Kimura 1995) are well worth perusal.

Theodosius Dobzhansky (1901-1975). Copyright Genetics Society of America

Texts

There are basically two types of population genetics texts - the comprehensive and the overview. The classic in the former category is J. F. Crow and Kimura (1964); there are those who argue that anyone who wants to acquire a deep and basic understadning of the subject should start by digesting this in its entirety. It is, however, more than fifty years old, and much has happened since then. For more modern takes, see Hamilton (2009), Charlesworth and Charlesworth, or Hedrick (2004).

The shorter versions tend to be much more accessible, however that can be both a blessing and a curse, as often they overdo compression of difficult concepts. The classic in this genre is Mettler and Gregg; Three others worthy of note are J. G. Crow (1986), Gillespie (2006) and Hartl and Clark (2006). The most recent of these books, Nielsen and Slatkin (2013), is one that we will refer to regularly as we progress.

Finally, Joe Felsenstein has produced a comprehensive online treatment of theoretical population genetics (Felsenstein 2015). It is free of charge and can be downloaded as a pdf file. We will refer to this often - indeed it can be considered a companion volume, providing the theoretical background that we will frequently gloss over.

For a quick overview of the main themes of Felsenstein see http://evolution.gs.washington.edu/gecco.pdf
